AB  - On board the ISS, remote ultrasound sessions enable physicians to monitor, from ground, the evolution of the human body through extended microgravity exposure. As the space exploration will guide us further away from Earth, delay will impact real time interaction and tele operated systems will no longer be usable. Our objective was to design a solution which allows a novice to locate the probe on the acoustic window and to get a medically usable view of any organ without any assistance. Our solution uses an augmented reality application to assist the novice operator in performing an echography. Before flight, the software enables an expert sonographer to save the cartesian probe coordinates corresponding to the perfect position and orientation of an ultrasound probe to get the perfect 2D echographic image of an organ. In-flight, the novice operator is able to retrieve the probe's position registered preflight thanks to an augmented reality visualization on the subject body. The protocol has been tested on a 3-day parabolic flight campaign. The solution allowed to find the AW in 88% and a 2D image in 82% of the 34 organs investigated. This tool will allow a reliable ultrasound medical surveillance during long distance space trip with no realtime link with earth. Its usage may be extended to isolated areas and medical deserts that cannot benefit from the precious tool that is ultrasonography. Copyright © 2022 by the International Astronautical Federation (IAF). All rights reserved.
