AB  - This article presents the project carried out by Tecnored's specialized team in order to design and commercialize an energy supply system for irrigation by using photovoltaic energy. This system aims to small farmers in Chile seek the water resource, particularly those in isolated areas which suffer from the problem of the prolonged "mega-drought" that has affected the country since 2010, furthermore the irrigation methods used are not very accessible. In this context, this article accounts for the technological solutions to the irrigation system powered by photovoltaic system that Tecnored has designed to supply energy for small farmers who are out of connection to the grid, contrasting their advantages, disadvantages, and installation costs, with focus on supplying electricity for a daytime irrigation system for 10 years. The study shows that, due to its modularity, ease of maintenance, long service life and low cost, as well as Chile's unique solar conditions, and the government incentives, photovoltaic technology with variable frequency inverters is the most suitable choice for small farmer far from the grid. In addition, the solution is consistent with Chile's commitment to Climate Change and is the most commercially attractive one, which can add product value to clean agricultural production. © The Institution of Engineering and Technology.
