AB  - The increasing demand for bandwidth with predictions of up to 1000 times more data required from 2010 to 2020 and a continuous growth expected from 2020 to 2030, according to the ITU, of video and M2M traffic, has been the definitively impulse for the changes in the satellite communication industry. The role of the Satcom in 5G and in the internet of things is beyond the classical satellite usages and customers. The Satcom plays a key role by extending the coverage of the terrestrial networks, providing connection for maritime, aircrafts and isolated areas; relieving the traffic congestion and providing added resilience for critical applications. The revolution in the satellite communication industry has become evident in the past few years. We are witnessing a raise of new constellations such as O3B or OneWeb, the renovation of the Iridium fleet, etc. Meanwhile in the ground segment, manufacturers of equipments are competing to deliver more efficient modulations supported by cheaper, smaller and easier to deploy units. If we look at the geostationary orbit, the satellites operators are struggling to offer higher throughput and improved adaptive solutions to reduce the cost per bit. In addition, the innovations in satellite platforms with more precise AOCS, and more capacity of batteries and solar cells, 3D printout circuits and also with the massive production of small satellites using assembly-line-based manufacturing processes such as OneWeb and the availability of new commercial launchers will definitively and completely change the commercial space industry. Many solutions have been tested in the past few years to enhance flexibility of the satellite communications, in particular in the traditional geostationary orbit. A flexible payload can be reconfigured in several ways as for example by modifying the coverage areas, each transponder power or the frequency and bandwidth of each channel, being the recent Quantum satellite (an ESA’s ARTES program) a good example. A payload that fulfils the three adaptive capacities (coverage, channel power and channel frequency plus bandwidth) shall allow the satellites operators to completely redefine the mission once in orbit either to adapt it to a changing demand or in case of moving the satellite to a different orbital slot. In classical missions the payload requirements are already almost fixed a few years before the launch and remains fixed during 15 years or even more while in-orbit. The payload is designed to provide the specified service in a designated area and therefore the main tasks of the satellite operators, as far as the payload operations are concerned, consist in dealing with interferences sources, meteorology events and satellite components aging, solar panels and TWTAs, which shall require eventually increasing/decreasing the operational point of the transponders or switching to a spare unit in case of failure of a nominal one and, if the payload support this, changing the uplink to downlink connectivity. Flexible payloads include the dynamic modification in the transmission plan in response to users changing demands as a new variable in regular operations, which shall have a great impact in the way payload operations need to be handled driving the need of automation with support for managing the interactions among the payload subsystems. Another concept that changes completely from fixed missions to flexible ones is the spare unit management. This, being a basic concept when designing, building and operating the fixed payload, fades away in the flexible payloads where no units are designed as spare equipment. This paper focus on the changes in payload operation concepts from traditional geostationary missions to flexible payload ones and the ground systems required to efficiently operate a flexible payload maximizing the provided capacity. Main requirements for an in-flight mission design, link budget and payload management tool are exposed, and finally, GMV smart payload suite is introduced as a possible solution focusing on how to fulfil the presented requirements and a possible evolution of the suite for carrier monitoring using the capabilities of a flexible payload. © 2018, American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics Inc, AIAA. All rights reserved.
